1.
Question 1
You plan on creating an Azure Storage Account that will contain queues. Which type of Storage Account can you consider?

Select all options that apply.

1 / 1 point

General-Purpose Storage Accounts v1

Correct
Queues are available as part of Azure general-purpose Storage Accounts v1.


Blob Storage Accounts 


General-Purpose Storage Accounts v2

Correct
Queues are available as part of Azure general-purpose Storage Accounts v2.

2.
Question 2
Which authorization methods can you use to successfully make requests to a queue?

Select all options that apply.

0 / 1 point

Service Credentials

This should not be selected
Queues do not have this type of authorization method available.


Azure Active Directory 


Shared Access Signature 

Correct
You can use a generated URI that grants limited access to objects in your storage account to clients.


Shared Key 

Correct
You can use the encrypted key signature associated with the storage account.

3.
Question 3
You are developing an application that needs programmatic access to your queue. Which type from the Azure Storage Client Library for .NET represents a queue instance?

1 / 1 point

CloudQueueClient


CloudQueue 


CloudStorageAccount 

Correct
CloudQueue represents one of your queue instances.

4.
Question 4
You are developing an application that needs to programmatically send a message from a queue. Which object should you instantiate to perform this action? 

1 / 1 point

CloudQueue


CloudQueueClient


CloudQueueMessage

Correct
CloudQueueMessage represents a message.

5.
Question 5
Which pieces of information do you need to access a queue?

Select all options that apply.

1 / 1 point

Authorization Token

Correct
The Authorization Token is needed to access a queue.


Storage Account Name

Correct
The Storage Account Name is needed to access a queue.


Shared Key


Queue Name

Correct
The Queue Name is needed to access a queue.
